SIMPLE: pike
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pike
<hw>Pike</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>pique</ets>;
perhaps of Celtic origin; cf. W. <ets>pig</ets> a prick, a point, beak,
Arm. <ets>pik</ets> pick. But cf. also L. <ets>picus</ets> woodpecker
(see <er>Pie</er> magpie), and E. <ets>spike</ets>. Cf. <er>Pick</er>,
<pos>n. & v.</pos>, <er>Peak</er>, <er>Pique</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A foot soldier's weapon, consisting of a long
wooden shaft or staff, with a pointed steel head. It is now superseded
by the bayonet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A pointed head or spike; esp., one in the center of
a shield or target.</def> <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A hayfork.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A pick.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wright. Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A pointed or peaked hill.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A large haycock.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A turnpike; a toll bar.</def>
<rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <pos>sing. & pl.</pos> <def>A large
fresh-water fish (<spn>Esox lucius</spn>), found in Europe and America,
highly valued as a food fish; -- called also
<altname>pickerel</altname>, <altname>gedd</altname>,
<altname>luce</altname>, and <altname>jack</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Blue pike</xex>, <xex>grass pike</xex>, <xex>green
pike</xex>, <xex>wall-eyed pike</xex>, and <xex>yellow pike</xex>, are
names, not of true pike, but of the wall-eye. See
<er>Wall-eye</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gar pike</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Gar</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Pike perch</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any fresh-water
fish of the genus <gen>Stizostedion</gen> (formerly
<gen>Lucioperca</gen>). See <er>Wall-eye</er>, and <er>Sauger</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Pike pole</b></col>, <cd>a long pole with a pike in one end,
used in directing floating logs.</cd> -- <col><b>Pike whale</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a finback whale of the North Atlantic
(<spn>Bal⟦ae⟧noptera rostrata</spn>), having an elongated snout; --
called also <altname>piked whale</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sand
pike</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the lizard fish.</cd> --
<col><b>Sea pike</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the garfish
<sd>(a)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piked</ent>⟦br⟧
